become practitioners and promoters of Daoism. Throughout are lively portrayals of encounters among the book’s various characters—Chinese hermits and monks, Western seekers, and scholar-practitioners—as they interact with each other in obtuse, often humorous, and yet sometimes enlightening and transformative ways. Dream Trippers untangles the anxieties, confusions, and ambiguities that arise as Chinese and American practitioners balance cosmological attunement and radical spiritual individualism in their search for authenticity in a globalized world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aGlobalizationxReligious aspectsxTaoism. 0aPilgrims and pilgrimageszChinazHua Mountain (Shaanxi Sheng) 0aPilgrims and pilgrimageszChinazHua Mountain (Shaanxi Sheng). 0aSpiritualityxTaoism. 0aTaoismzUnited States. 0aTaoism. 0aTaoistszChina. 0aTaoistszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aChina.  aDaoism.  aNew Age.  aauthenticity.  aglobalization.  amonasticism.  aqigong.  areligion.  aspirituality.  atourism.1 aPalmer, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSiegler, Elijah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSiegler, Elijah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022648176040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226484983423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226484983/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles